Any feels on a collaborative blog on reactivecocoaiohttpreactivecocoaio  In separate discussions with indragiek and Coneko we each feel we should write more about RAC because we have insights and experiences to share With a couple of exceptions most of us arent prolific writers but maybe collectively we can have a good thing There have been a bunch of people writing about RAC lately how does everyone feel about those Should RAC have an official speaker box  Obviously such a blog can live anywhere I just wanted to see what the feels are about having it on reactivecocoaiohttpreactivecocoaio  Related to ReactiveCocoaReactiveCocoa1162   cc ReactiveCocoareactivecocoa jonsterling

Part of what has made adopting RAC enjoyable has been the number of community projects that have sprung up that RACize existing APIs both Apples and community supported  It occurred to me that maintaining a list pseudoofficial list of ReactiveCocoaenabled libraries might be beneficial to newcomers and increase awareness of the RAC ecosystem as a whole  Assuming ReactiveCocoa thinks this is a good idea Id be happy to open a PR  My only question would be what is the most appropriate location  The ReactiveCocoa repo itself possibly in Readmemd  Or something less connected to the core library like ReactiveCocoaReactiveCocoagithubioReactiveCocoaReactiveCocoagithubio  Some libraries I hand in mind for initial inclusion CodaFiAFNetworkingRACExtensionsCodaFiAFNetworkingRACExtensions kastiglioneParseRACExtensionskastiglioneParseRACExtensions jonsterlingReactiveFormletsjonsterlingReactiveFormlets MattCBowmanReactiveCoreBluetoothMattCBowmanReactiveCoreBluetooth full disclosure author is my coworker

Ive had this on my personal todo list for a while but havent figured out exactly what to do yet Basically epatey made the excellent suggestion that its hard for users of and contributors to RAC to really know where its going without some kind of roadmap document  From my standpoint this also has the unfortunate side effect of bottlenecking on joshaber or I If we could define our vision for the framework in one place and break down the stages to get there it would be easier to parallelizeoutsource pieces of that  A roadmap could include anyall of   1 Extremely fuzzy dates to help answer queries like My project is gonna ship in 3 months Which RAC version should I use  1 Design goalsdirection so implementation effort can proceed even if were not available to give the seal of approval  1 Large pieces of outstanding work like a very highlevel answer to What would it take to ship 30  I dunno just brainstorming Does any of that make sense Anything else to add  cc ReactiveCocoareactivecocoa

At the moment I find it hard to browse code on the Github repo I think we should consider adding a folder structure to make browsing Moya on Github a better experience  I would keep everything the same but introduce a new Moya folder that contains all the relevant files    Demo  docs  web  Moya  Endpointswift  Moyaswift  MoyaResponseswift  ReactiveCocoa  MoyaReactiveCocoaswift  RACSignalMoyaswift  RxSwift  MoyaRxSwiftswift  READMEmd  Moyapodspec  etc   Thoughts

Given that components are fully decoupled or mostly at least as I havent checked every classes it would make sense to distribute them as separate Composer packages to allow users to depend only on the part they need For the bundle it would also allow to define its real dependencies instead of listing them as suggest in the global composerjson and having the bundle break if they are not installed it breaks if DoctrineBundle is not there btw and DoctrineBundle is not even listed Optional requirements are always a pain to manage because you cannot put any constraint about the version of the other package to be used well you could do some stuff with conflicts but it is not easy  there is 2 alternatives for this  1 develop in the main repo and then provide subtreesplits for each component This is the way Symfony does it It requires having a hook updating the subtrees each time the main repo gets updated     Pros  Cons          All development in one place  Complex to setup    Easy to testchange coupled parts  Release cycle is coupled   2 develop each component in their own repo dropping the main repo after creating subtree splits     Pros  Cons          Easy to setup no updating server needed  development is split in several places    Each component can be released separately when needed  harder to change coupled parts in nonBC ways    Easy for contributors to contribute on the component they use    Given that there is almost no coupling between components the second alternative probably wins in this case

Currently the crawler is running synchronously meaning that it spends most of its time waiting for IO Using an asynchronous HTTP client would allow being much more efficient by doing HTTP calls in parallel  Note that the asynchronous behavior can be implemented in a fully BC way crawlercrawl could still block until all URLs have been crawled and the callbackbased API can be kept the same  This means that instead of using Goutte to send the calls you would need to use Guzzle directly to be able to access its asynchronous APIhttpdocsguzzlephporgenlatestfaqhtmlcanguzzlesendasynchronousrequests You could then convert the response back to a BrowserKit response before calling the callback if you want to keep BC or you could decide to break BC and to pass a Guzzle response instead

follow up to httpsgithubcomsymfonysymfonyissues12401  in the CMF project we have encountered some bugs with 53 that we cannot work around mostly with image manipulation Also 53 can cause issues with memory consumption with composer  Also as long as Symfony core supports 53 we kind of also imply we expect the same from our eco system If however our ecosystem starts using 54 more then it will become more confusing for our users Especially hosters even internal IT might claim that 53 is good enough because its supported by Symfony core  so I think its worth thinking about moving to 54 even if there are no specific features we intend to use from 54 we can of course provide traits without moving to 54

A very nice to have would be a Vagrant setup for React  Someone looking to poke around with React but not ready to install libs on their system  Recipes would include   composer  PHP 54 with extensions  libevent  PHP libevent extension 005  libev  PHP libev extension travis examplehttpsgithubcomreactphpreactphpbloblooplibevtravisyml  ZeroMQ  PHP ZeroMQ bindings travis examplehttpsgithubcomreactphpzmqblobmastertravisyml  Not sure if this would be in vagrant of React repo or a separate sandbox repo  open to suggestions   Edit Links fixed Edit2 Removed dual PHP installation

Very specific title huh  The current implementation of reduxreactrouter works fine It meets the primary goals of  1 storing router state inside the Redux store 2 triggering transitions using an action creator 3 interoperability with normal React Router API Link  4 reacting to external state changes like the Redux Devtools  However the way its implemented is far from ideal For one its fragile  it relies on internal details of React Router which could easily change in a nonbreaking release  Ill try to explain what the problem is and some ways it could potentially be solved   The problem  The crux of the problem is that we need a way to access the router instance from outside of React The History object isnt enough Specifically we need   access to the current params  ability to call transitionTo  Another problem is that in order to trigger route transitions using a Redux action creator goal 2 above we need to wrap the dispatch method of the Redux store to intercept specific actions This is called middlewarehttpsgithubcomgaearonreduxblobimprovedocsdocstypesandterminologymdmiddleware and is a common pattern for extending Redux The problem is that this middleware requires access to the router which again is only accessible from inside a component This essentially means that the store passed to reduxRouteComponentstore ends up being different than the actual store that is added to React context in lieu of a Provider This is a bit hard to explain if youre not familiar with how Redux works but check out these lines to get an idea of what I mean httpsgithubcomacdlitereduxreactrouterblobmastersrcreduxRouteComponentjsL41L42  Ideally we could apply this middleware outside of React like any other Redux extension   Current API  js Router historyhistory   Route componentreduxRouteComponentstore       app routes go here   Route Router    Ideal API  Use a higherorder storehttpsgithubcomgaearonreduxblobimprovedocsdocshigherorderstoresmd which uses middleware internally  js const store  reduxReactRouterroutercreateStorereducer  or more likely compose with other higherorder stores const store  compose   applyMiddlewarepromise thunk   reduxReactRouterrouter   devTools reducer   This would require the router instance to have some sort of subscription API so we could listen for changes Eg   js routersubscribelocation params       do stuff    In lieu of an API like this right now were using componentWillReceiveProps to listen for changes which leads to unncessary render cycles This is partially addressed by using ReactaddonsbatchedUpdates but thats a workaround not a solution   Possible solution  With the current API the router instance and the Router component instance are the same thing Would it be possible to separate them into two parts one part that subscribes to history changes and does the route matching and the other part that does purely Reacty things like rendering Something like this  js const router  createRouter history  Router routerrouter    This may not even need to be a breaking change If the router prop is omitted the router instance could be created internally  Im not familiar enough with the codebase to know if this is actually possible just throwing out suggestions

Summary Right now if a component specifies a propType as for example myProp ReactPropTypesshape without an actual shape parameter any prop type will be accepted because ReactPropTypesshape returns a function the actual validator not an Error indicating that propType checking passed  This can create an unfortunate situation where a component looks like it has fully specified propTypes but in fact does not  This commit addresses this by making ReactPropTypesshape et al warn if they are passed arguments from propType checking rather than the single argument expected at creation time  Alternatively we could check that only null or instances of Error are returned from propType functions but given there is a test case testing that this is not true for custom components I wasnt sure if that was the right way to implement this  Test Plan Added unit tests ran jest in the root repo directory Also ran grunt lint and grunt test

I shipped jstransform 011 which now has the CLI and API from reacttools The intention was to deprecate reacttools entirely so we have 1 less thing to support and it lets us ship transform updates outside the React release cycle Im not sure if we just wont ship reacttools 014 at all or if itll basically reship jstransform  If youre a hawk and watching this repo and wondering what that means for you here are your options  Switch to jstranform I wrote a migration guidehttpsgithubcomfacebookjstransformmigrationguide for you  Switch to babel It supports many of the same things jstransform does and more  Do nothing We dont really suggest this but its an option We wont unship reacttools from npm so as long as you used versions correctly you should be able to keep chugging along   x remove transforms from here  x make sure our build still works  x make a reacttools that still works like the one we have  x make sure JSXTransformer still works did not make a new one of these for jstranform

Given that components are fully decoupled or mostly at least as I havent checked every classes it would make sense to distribute them as separate Composer packages to allow users to depend only on the part they need For the bundle it would also allow to define its real dependencies instead of listing them as suggest in the global composerjson and having the bundle break if they are not installed it breaks if DoctrineBundle is not there btw and DoctrineBundle is not even listed Optional requirements are always a pain to manage because you cannot put any constraint about the version of the other package to be used well you could do some stuff with conflicts but it is not easy  there is 2 alternatives for this  1 develop in the main repo and then provide subtreesplits for each component This is the way Symfony does it It requires having a hook updating the subtrees each time the main repo gets updated     Pros  Cons          All development in one place  Complex to setup    Easy to testchange coupled parts  Release cycle is coupled   2 develop each component in their own repo dropping the main repo after creating subtree splits     Pros  Cons          Easy to setup no updating server needed  development is split in several places    Each component can be released separately when needed  harder to change coupled parts in nonBC ways    Easy for contributors to contribute on the component they use    Given that there is almost no coupling between components the second alternative probably wins in this case

Currently the crawler is running synchronously meaning that it spends most of its time waiting for IO Using an asynchronous HTTP client would allow being much more efficient by doing HTTP calls in parallel  Note that the asynchronous behavior can be implemented in a fully BC way crawlercrawl could still block until all URLs have been crawled and the callbackbased API can be kept the same  This means that instead of using Goutte to send the calls you would need to use Guzzle directly to be able to access its asynchronous APIhttpdocsguzzlephporgenlatestfaqhtmlcanguzzlesendasynchronousrequests You could then convert the response back to a BrowserKit response before calling the callback if you want to keep BC or you could decide to break BC and to pass a Guzzle response instead

follow up to httpsgithubcomsymfonysymfonyissues12401  in the CMF project we have encountered some bugs with 53 that we cannot work around mostly with image manipulation Also 53 can cause issues with memory consumption with composer  Also as long as Symfony core supports 53 we kind of also imply we expect the same from our eco system If however our ecosystem starts using 54 more then it will become more confusing for our users Especially hosters even internal IT might claim that 53 is good enough because its supported by Symfony core  so I think its worth thinking about moving to 54 even if there are no specific features we intend to use from 54 we can of course provide traits without moving to 54

A very nice to have would be a Vagrant setup for React  Someone looking to poke around with React but not ready to install libs on their system  Recipes would include   composer  PHP 54 with extensions  libevent  PHP libevent extension 005  libev  PHP libev extension travis examplehttpsgithubcomreactphpreactphpbloblooplibevtravisyml  ZeroMQ  PHP ZeroMQ bindings travis examplehttpsgithubcomreactphpzmqblobmastertravisyml  Not sure if this would be in vagrant of React repo or a separate sandbox repo  open to suggestions   Edit Links fixed Edit2 Removed dual PHP installation

Port 8081 is currently used by reactnative as the debugging port in the following files   LibrariesRCTTestRCTTestRunnerm LibrariesWebSocketRCTWebSocketExecutorm ReactBaseRCTRedBoxm ReactReactxcodeprojprojectpbxproj   Unfortunately there are other services that might use 8081 ie McAfee  Port  Default  Description  Traffic direction          Agent wakeup communication port SuperAgent repository port   8081  TCP port that agents use to receive agent wakeup requests from the ePO server or Agent Handler  Inbound connection from the ePO serverAgent Handler to the McAfee Agent   See httpskcmcafeecomcorporateindexpagecontentidKB66797  Another reason for having a configurable reactnative debug port is that I often work on two reactnative projects in parallel ie my own project plus UIExplorer But both reactnative apps collide because both want to use port 8081  Please make reactnatives debug port configurable in order to avoid conflicts with other services

The assemblies built in this project are not strongname signed This makes them unconsumable on NET Framework from assemblies that are themselves strongname signed  If you strongname sign your assemblies work everywhere If you dont strongname sign your assemblies only work for folks who dont strongname sign

MvvmCross recently switched its codebindings to a Fluent binding class  httpsgithubcomslodgeMvvmCrossblobv3CirriousCirriousMvvmCrossBindingBindingContextMvxFluentBindingDescriptioncs  This meant that binding code in MonoTouch went from        thisBind thisGo HomeViewModel vm  vmCommandsSearch       thisBind thisRandom HomeViewModel vm  vmCommandsPickRandom       thisBind thisEdit HomeViewModel vm  vmSearchText  to        thisCreateBindingthisGoToHomeViewModelvm  vmCommandsSearchApply       thisCreateBindingthisRandomToHomeViewModelvm  vmCommandsPickRandomApply       thisCreateBindingthisEditToHomeViewModelvm  vmSearchTextApply     At a user level this made the bindings   a bit more verbose not always a good thing  much more intellisense friendly a good thing  usable in new ways  because you could create the binding once and Apply it multiple times  More significantly for me at a platform level this meant I could maintain and extend MvvmCross much more The current tutorial shows no server so a user cannot complete the steps posting JSON by following the instructions  Also per issue 603 users get the mistaken impression they need jQuery  This patch adds sample code for a python server and additional explanations as to what the application expects from a server

Since the tutorial describes doing things either in the browser or in node it doesnt make sense to advocate using python m SimpleHTTPServer Instead it makes more sense to tell people to run npm install g httpserver and to then use the much simple httpserver command to fire up a localhost instance on port 8080 in whatever directory they run it in

We have been running into problems recently with the bower release not being as usable as the npm release primarily due to the different distribution mechanism that bower proposes  Seeing as React as well as many Bower packages only provide the concatenated and minified build output Im inclined to do the same here  Pros   Easier to maintain since dependency differences between the two will be less complicated  React addonsutils can be cherrypicked as needed and not committed to this repo  Allow us to use babelruntimehttpbabeljsiodocsusageruntime without declaring it as a bower dependency  Use requirebabelcorepolyfill in Interpolatejs and OverlayTriggerjs and remove babelpluginobjectassign dependency  Cons   Bower users will be forced to load the entire library all the time They will not be able to optimize their release  This will complicate the reactrouterbootstrap bower release and source Will be resolved by reactbootstrapreactrouterbootstrap74  My questions for bower users since I dont personally use it   What is bower gaining you that you cant get with npm  What would you expect from a bower package  What am I missing here

Very specific title huh  The current implementation of reduxreactrouter works fine It meets the primary goals of  1 storing router state inside the Redux store 2 triggering transitions using an action creator 3 interoperability with normal React Router API Link  4 reacting to external state changes like the Redux Devtools  However the way its implemented is far from ideal For one its fragile  it relies on internal details of React Router which could easily change in a nonbreaking release  Ill try to explain what the problem is and some ways it could potentially be solved   The problem  The crux of the problem is that we need a way to access the router instance from outside of React The History object isnt enough Specifically we need   access to the current params  ability to call transitionTo  Another problem is that in order to trigger route transitions using a Redux action creator goal 2 above we need to wrap the dispatch method of the Redux store to intercept specific actions This is called middlewarehttpsgithubcomgaearonreduxblobimprovedocsdocstypesandterminologymdmiddleware and is a common pattern for extending Redux The problem is that this middleware requires access to the router which again is only accessible from inside a component This essentially means that the store passed to reduxRouteComponentstore ends up being different than the actual store that is added to React context in lieu of a Provider This is a bit hard to explain if youre not familiar with how Redux works but check out these lines to get an idea of what I mean httpsgithubcomacdlitereduxreactrouterblobmastersrcreduxRouteComponentjsL41L42  Ideally we could apply this middleware outside of React like any other Redux extension   Current API  js Router historyhistory   Route componentreduxRouteComponentstore       app routes go here   Route Router    Ideal API  Use a higherorder storehttpsgithubcomgaearonreduxblobimprovedocsdocshigherorderstoresmd which uses middleware internally  js const store  reduxReactRouterroutercreateStorereducer  or more likely compose with other higherorder stores const store  compose   applyMiddlewarepromise thunk   reduxReactRouterrouter   devTools reducer   This would require the router instance to have some sort of subscription API so we could listen for changes Eg   js routersubscribelocation params       do stuff    In lieu of an API like this right now were using componentWillReceiveProps to listen for changes which leads to unncessary render cycles This is partially addressed by using ReactaddonsbatchedUpdates but thats a workaround not a solution   Possible solution  With the current API the router instance and the Router component instance are the same thing Would it be possible to separate them into two parts one part that subscribes to history changes and does the route matching and the other part that does purely Reacty things like rendering Something like this  js const router  createRouter history  Router routerrouter    This may not even need to be a breaking change If the router prop is omitted the router instance could be created internally  Im not familiar enough with the codebase to know if this is actually possible just throwing out suggestions

Summary Right now if a component specifies a propType as for example myProp ReactPropTypesshape without an actual shape parameter any prop type will be accepted because ReactPropTypesshape returns a function the actual validator not an Error indicating that propType checking passed  This can create an unfortunate situation where a component looks like it has fully specified propTypes but in fact does not  This commit addresses this by making ReactPropTypesshape et al warn if they are passed arguments from propType checking rather than the single argument expected at creation time  Alternatively we could check that only null or instances of Error are returned from propType functions but given there is a test case testing that this is not true for custom components I wasnt sure if that was the right way to implement this  Test Plan Added unit tests ran jest in the root repo directory Also ran grunt lint and grunt test

fehmicansaglam By default the read preference is primary and some times its needed for us to change it to primary preferred or others provided by reactive mongo This PR adds the default preference to be primary but allows for overriding at class level or provide as argument at method level Note that I had to change findAllIds to take a Seq instead of vararg as Scala does not allow any other method arguments to have a default parameter with vararg  Since this is my first PR against this repo please do let me know if it is against a wrong branch or if it didnt follow some process  Do let me know if you want me to change anything I implemented here would be happy to contribute  Thanks

Im using reactdnd for a kanban board app trello like and when moving a card to another list thus unmounting source component during drag the endDrag function is not called as the listeners for DragDropStore are removed on unmount  As a workaround Ive added a _lastDraggedItem and getLastDraggedItem to DragDropStore and subscribed to DragDropStore on parent component handling the endDrag there As we clear the variables in DragDropStore before firing the DRAG_END event I couldnt find any other way to get dragged item  The reason Im not using DROP event is its not fired when the item is dropped outside of browser window only DRAG_END is fired  It works but its messy breaking the beginDrag  endDrag symmetry  Are there any other ways to trigger a function on endDrag with access to dragged item   Or if is this a valid usecase for others should we add my workaround to the repo

First reactselect is slick Its been awesome to work with Ive been wanting to make some bugfixes but have ended up with my hands tied because of a few things that are hard to reason about This list also contains some other notes     Drop the dist files altogether Reacts already basically impossible to use without a bundler so Im not sure if its doing much good Please dont update the dist files gets really old to say to the million people who dont read the contributing notes    Build lib when publishing but ignore in repo same point as above    Reducereconsider usage of componentWillMount Its triggered on the server so calling autoloadAsyncOptions and such here seems strange Also Im not sure this_bindCloseMenuIfClickedOutside   etc are assigned in this way here    Enforce options prop to be immutable Whenever a prop changes theres two JSONstringify calls in componentWillReceiveProps that are expensive for large datasets Itd be more efficient if there could just be a strict equality check here    Move functionality not directly related to the control out to separate filesmodules The includes       DOM event binding       Option searching for selectizehttpsgithubcombrianreavisselectizejs I split this out to sifterjshttpsgithubcombrianreavissifterjs because it ballooned and needlessly complicated the library    Consolidate menu opening code to happen in one spot As it is right now the menus events are bound multiple places throughout the library I think the intent is to consolidate setState calls React will batch these so I thinks a bit moot and leading to more problems than its solving Its tough to track down where events are boundunbound    Dont modify state directly esp in render methods eg L630L634httpsgithubcomJedWatsonreactselectblobmastersrcSelectjsL630L634    Use spread in cases like thesehttpsgithubcomJedWatsonreactselectblobmastersrcSelectjsL737L741    Why does the this context matter on callbacks Eg callbackcallthis  All React element methods are autobound already    Consider httpsgithubcomJedWatsonreactselectissues25 Given that Reacts point is abstracting away DOM craziness I think that the values must be strings is quite limiting it leads to lots of applicationlevel casting in onChange events It feels very weird to cast an ID to a string for Select then cast it back to a number  JedWatson dcousens What are your thoughts on these I almost started on a lot of these today but itll create a lot of merge conflicts on existing PRs and be a little risky wo tests
